OpenAI Dev Newsletter

Welcome to the OpenAI developer update=E2=80=94your source for what=E2=80=
=99s shipping, how teams are building, and practical guidance straight from=
 our engineers.

Not in our Discord ( http://discord.gg/openai ) yet? Join to hear directly =
from us and stay in touch with the OpenAI developer community.

=E2=9A=A1 What's new

What shipped, what changed, what to automate next

*
Your new command center for agentic coding*
The Codex app is designed for multi-tasking with agents ( https://openai.co=
m/index/introducing-the-codex-app/ ) and connects to all your tools. Superv=
ise parallel workstreams, review changes cleanly, and stay in control from =
background execution to shipped code.=C2=A0And for a limited time, try Code=
x ( https://openai.com/codex/ ) in ChatGPT Free and ChatGPT Go.

*Make Codex smarter everywhere
* GPT-5.3-Codex can make Codex a more autonomous coworker ( https://openai.=
com/index/introducing-gpt-5-3-codex/ ) across all Codex surfaces: the app, =
CLI, IDE extensions, and web=E2=80=94and is now available in the Responses =
API, too. We also released a research preview of GPT-5.3-Codex-Spark, a sma=
ller, faster model built for real-time coding. ( https://openai.com/index/i=
ntroducing-gpt-5-3-codex-spark/ )

*Speed up tool-heavy agent runs with WebSockets
* WebSockets in the Responses API speed up agent runs by 20=E2=80=9340% ( h=
ttps://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/websocket-mode ) by maintainin=
g a persistent connection=E2=80=94so you only send new inputs instead of fu=
ll context each turn.

*Build longer-running agents with the API
* We=E2=80=99ve added an OpenAI-hosted container (with networking), Skills,=
 and automatic compaction to the Responses API. This enables long-running w=
orkflows ( https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/tools-shell ) on c=
omputers that execute tasks more reliably ( https://developers.openai.com/a=
pi/docs/guides/tools-skills ) and work across millions of tokens ( https://=
developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/compaction ).

*Upgrade your Realtime voice stack*
If you=E2=80=99re building voice agents, gpt-realtime-1.5 is the new defaul=
t ( https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/realtime/ ) stronger mult=
ilingual conversation, tighter instruction following, and more reliable too=
l calling.

*Generate images in bulk with the Batch API
* You can now use the Batch API with our gpt-image models to send async gro=
ups of requests at 50% lower cost ( https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/=
guides/batch ) , with access to a separate pool of higher rate limits. This=
 is available for our gpt-image models ( https://developers.openai.com/api/=
docs/guides/image-generation ) : gpt-image-1.5, chatgpt-image-latest, gpt-i=
mage-1, and gpt-image-1-mini.

=F0=9F=A7=B0 Build kit

Guides, blogs, and things worth cloning

*Automate the repetitive stuff:* Andrew from the Codex engineering team sho=
ws how he uses Codex Automations to offload recurring tasks ( https://www.y=
outube.com/watch?v=3DxHnlzAPD9QI ) =E2=80=94what to automate, how to set it=
 up, and where it saves real time.

*Work on two things at once (without chaos):* Joey from the Codex engineeri=
ng team demos parallel development with Codex worktrees: delegate a feature=
 in one worktree, keep coding in another, then review and land both PRs. Pa=
rallel workflows turn waiting time into progress. ( https://www.youtube.com=
/watch?v=3D9ohXlkbXiM4 )

*Build agents that can run for hours:* Shell tool, Skills, and automatic Co=
mpaction are the core primitives for long-running agents. Get our tips for =
practical patterns ( https://developers.openai.com/blog/skills-shell-tips )=
 to execute commands, reuse behaviors, and keep context stable over time.

*Build agents that behave (and remember):* Two Cookbook articles break down=
 how prompt structure shapes agent behavior and reliability ( https://cookb=
ook.openai.com/examples/gpt-5/prompt_personalities ) and how context engine=
ering determines what gets retained vs. dropped ( https://cookbook.openai.c=
om/examples/agents_sdk/context_personalization ).

*Did your agent improve... or just change?:* Evals turn =E2=80=9Cfeels bett=
er=E2=80=9D into actual checks. ( https://developers.openai.com/blog/eval-s=
kills ) Did the skill trigger, do the right thing, and leave things clean? =
This will help you catch regressions early.

*Stop recomputing the same prompts:* Prompt caching reuses shared prefixes =
( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3DtECAkJAI_Vk ) to make AI apps faster an=
d cheaper at scale.

=F0=9F=9B=A0=EF=B8=8F Devs in the wild

From side projects to professional work

*Company spotlight: Skyscanner*

By wiring the Codex CLI into JetBrains ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3D=
1XkVsE9-ZK4 ) IDEs via the Model Context Protocol (MCP), Skyscanner gave Co=
dex access to real IDE context ( https://developers.openai.com/blog/skyscan=
ner-codex-jetbrains-mcp ). This unlocks smarter problem-solving, faster fee=
dback loops, and measurable gains in development speed.

*Developer spotlight: Agrim Singh*

Check out the full thread on X from Agrim ( https://x.com/agrimsingh/status=
/2022028612770443385 ) , CTO of Niyam AI (and Codex ambassador!) for an ear=
ly wl1 demo, the repo, and notes on the build.

=F0=9F=93=A3 Insider scoop

Go behind the scenes with OpenAI engineers

*Harness engineering ( https://openai.com/index/harness-engineering/ ) : le=
veraging Codex in an agent-first world*

Note from the author: =E2=80=9COur team has varied experience, and humans c=
an=E2=80=99t fully mind-meld. Codex can: when we encode =E2=80=98what good =
looks like=E2=80=99 in the repo, every run applies it consistently=E2=80=94=
and the gains compound.=E2=80=9D

- Ryan Lopopolo, Member of Technical Staff at OpenAI.=C2=A0Keep up with his=
 work on X ( https://x.com/_lopopolo ).

*Inside the Postgres Setup ( https://openai.com/index/scaling-postgresql/ )=
 Powering 800M ChatGPT Users*

Note from the author: =E2=80=9CBefore OpenAI, I learned the hard way that s=
tartups often over-engineer. Here, I=E2=80=99ve been impressed by how far a=
 deliberately simple setup=E2=80=94a single PostgreSQL writer=E2=80=94can s=
cale with the right optimizations and discipline. That inspired me to share=
 what I=E2=80=99ve seen.=E2=80=9D

- Bohan Zhang, Member of Technical Staff at OpenAI. K eep up with his work =
on X ( https://x.com/BohanZhangOT ).

*What Actually Happens Inside an AI Coding Agent ( https://openai.com/index=
/unrolling-the-codex-agent-loop/ ) (We Unrolled It)*

Note from the author: =E2=80=9CDespite being on Codex CLI since the beginni=
ng, I learned a lot from putting this post together, so hopefully you will,=
 too!=E2=80=9D

- Michael Bolin, Member of Technical Staff at OpenAI.=C2=A0Follow more of h=
is journey on Threads ( https://www.threads.com/@bolinfest/post/DT3cVLlkubK=
 ).

